        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">South Korean martial law</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-dec-4-2.jpg" alt="South Korean martial law" href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">South Korea faces significant political turmoil after President Yoon Suk Yeol <a href="https://edition.cnn.com/world/live-news/martial-law-south-korea-intl/index.html" target="_blank">declared martial law</a>, accusing the opposition of anti-state activities and ties to North Korea. The martial law decree, the first since 1980, bans political activities and parliamentary functions and allows warrantless arrests. In an emergency late-night session, all 190 lawmakers in the National Assembly unanimously voted to block the decree, and President Yoon said he would revoke the law after almost 6 hours of its declaration. Experts and opposition call for the <a href="https://news.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20241204050015" target="_blank">impeachment</a> of the president.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Even Yoon’s ruling People Power Party members criticized the move, calling for the decree to be rescinded. The opposition has called this illegal, violates the constitutional and other laws, and called it a coup d’état. While the nation calls for the president’s impeachment, the Chief of Staff Chung Jin-suk, National Advisor Shin Won-sik, and Presidential Chief of Staff for Policy Sung Tae-yoon, along with seven other senior aides have tendered their resignations.​</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="10px 12px" />
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
