          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">No confidence in France</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The French government faces a <a href="https://www.politico.eu/article/france-government-no-confidence-vote-planned-for-wednesday-michel-barnier-pm/" target="_blank">critical vote</a> on Wednesday as the National Assembly prepares to consider several no-confidence motions against Prime Minister Michel Barnier. These motions, driven by Barnier's controversial constitutional maneuver to pass a social security financial bill without parliament's approval using <a href="https://www.lemonde.fr/en/france/article/2022/10/19/france-how-does-article-49-3-allow-a-bill-to-be-passed-without-a-vote_6001019_7.html" target="_blank">Article 49.3</a>, are expected to succeed. The left-wing New Popular Front coalition and the far-right National Front both plan to vote against the government. This is likely to oust Barnier, making him the shortest-serving prime minister in modern French history since his appointment by President Emmanuel Macron in September.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">This would be the first no-confidence vote to topple a French government since 1962. However, even if this government falls apart, two elections can’t be held within a year of each other, so it would have to wait until July. It highlights France's escalating political crisis and raises concerns about political stability in the EU.</p>
        </mj-text>
